[{"text": "Space,", "start": 21.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "we all know what it looks like.", "start": 23.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "We've been surrounded by images of space", "start": 25.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "our whole lives,", "start": 27.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "from the speculative images", "start": 29.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "of science fiction", "start": 31.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to the inspirational visions of artists", "start": 33.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "to the increasingly beautiful pictures", "start": 36.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "made possible by complex technologies.", "start": 39.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "But whilst we have", "start": 42.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "an overwhelmingly vivid", "start": 44.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "visual understanding of space,", "start": 46.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "we have no sense of what space sounds like.", "start": 48.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "And indeed, most people associate space with silence.", "start": 51.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "But the story of how", "start": 55.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "we came to understand the universe", "start": 57.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "is just as much a story of listening", "start": 59.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "as it is by looking.", "start": 61.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "And yet despite this,", "start": 64.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "hardly any of us have ever heard space.", "start": 66.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "How many of you here", "start": 69.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "could describe the sound", "start": 71.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "of a single planet or star?", "start": 73.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Well in case you've ever wondered,", "start": 75.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "this is what the Sun sounds like.", "start": 77.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "(Static)", "start": 79.26, "duration": 14.0}, {"text": "(Crackling)", "start": 93.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "(Static)", "start": 97.26, "duration": 6.0}, {"text": "(Crackling)", "start": 103.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "This is the planet Jupiter.", "start": 107.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "(Soft crackling)", "start": 110.26, "duration": 20.0}, {"text": "And this is the space probe Cassini", "start": 130.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "pirouetting through the ice rings of Saturn.", "start": 133.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "(Crackling)", "start": 137.26, "duration": 20.0}, {"text": "This is a a highly condensed clump", "start": 157.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "of neutral matter,", "start": 160.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "spinning in the distant universe.", "start": 162.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "(Tapping)", "start": 166.26, "duration": 18.0}, {"text": "So my artistic practice", "start": 184.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "is all about listening", "start": 186.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to the weird and wonderful noises", "start": 188.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "emitted by the magnificent celestial objects", "start": 191.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "that make up our universe.", "start": 194.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "And you may wonder,", "start": 197.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "how do we know what these sounds are?", "start": 199.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "How can we tell the difference", "start": 201.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "between the sound of the Sun", "start": 203.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "and the sound of a pulsar?", "start": 205.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Well the answer", "start": 207.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "is the science of radio astronomy.", "start": 209.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Radio astronomers", "start": 211.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "study radio waves from space", "start": 213.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "using sensitive antennas and receivers,", "start": 215.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "which give them precise information", "start": 218.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "about what an astronomical object is", "start": 220.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "and where it is in our night sky.", "start": 223.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "And just like the signals", "start": 225.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "that we send and receive here on Earth,", "start": 227.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "we can convert these transmissions into sound", "start": 230.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "using simple analog techniques.", "start": 233.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "And therefore, it's through listening", "start": 236.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "that we've come to uncover", "start": 239.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "some of the universe's most important secrets --", "start": 241.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "its scale, what it's made of", "start": 244.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "and even how old it is.", "start": 247.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "So today, I'm going to tell you a short story", "start": 249.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "of the history of the universe through listening.", "start": 252.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "It's punctuated", "start": 255.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "by three quick anecdotes,", "start": 257.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "which show how accidental encounters", "start": 259.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "with strange noises", "start": 261.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "gave us some of the most important information", "start": 263.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "we have about space.", "start": 266.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Now this story doesn't start", "start": 268.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "with vast telescopes", "start": 270.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "or futuristic spacecraft,", "start": 272.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "but a rather more humble technology --", "start": 275.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "and in fact, the very medium", "start": 278.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "which gave us the telecommunications revolution", "start": 280.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "that we're all part of today:", "start": 283.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "the telephone.", "start": 285.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "It's 1876, it's in Boston,", "start": 287.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "and this is Alexander Graham Bell", "start": 290.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "who was working with Thomas Watson", "start": 292.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "on the invention of the telephone.", "start": 294.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "A key part of their technical set up", "start": 297.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "was a half-mile long length of wire,", "start": 300.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "which was thrown across the rooftops", "start": 302.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "of several houses in Boston.", "start": 304.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "The line carried the telephone signals", "start": 307.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "that would later make Bell a household name.", "start": 310.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "But like any long length of charged wire,", "start": 313.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "it also inadvertently became", "start": 316.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "an antenna.", "start": 318.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Thomas Watson", "start": 320.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "spent hours listening", "start": 322.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to the strange crackles and hisses", "start": 324.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "and chirps and whistles", "start": 326.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "that his accidental antenna detected.", "start": 329.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "Now you have to remember,", "start": 332.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "this is 10 years before", "start": 334.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Heinrich Hertz proved the existence of radio waves --", "start": 336.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "15 years before Nikola Tesla's four-tuned circuit --", "start": 340.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "nearly 20 years before Marconi's first broadcast.", "start": 343.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "So Thomas Watson wasn't listening to us.", "start": 347.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "We didn't have the technology", "start": 350.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to transmit.", "start": 352.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "So what were these strange noises?", "start": 354.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "Watson was in fact listening", "start": 358.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to very low-frequency radio emissions", "start": 360.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "caused by nature.", "start": 362.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Some of the crackles and pops were lightning,", "start": 364.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "but the eerie whistles", "start": 367.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "and curiously melodious chirps", "start": 370.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "had a rather more exotic origin.", "start": 373.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "Using the very first telephone,", "start": 376.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Watson was in fact", "start": 378.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "dialed into the heavens.", "start": 380.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "As he correctly guessed,", "start": 382.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "some of these sounds were caused", "start": 384.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "by activity on the surface of the Sun.", "start": 386.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "It was a solar wind", "start": 389.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "interacting with our ionosphere", "start": 391.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "that he was listening to --", "start": 393.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "a phenomena which we can see", "start": 395.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "at the extreme northern and southern latitudes of our planet", "start": 397.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "as the aurora.", "start": 400.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "So whilst inventing the technology", "start": 402.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "that would usher in the telecommunications revolution,", "start": 405.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "Watson had discovered", "start": 409.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "that the star at the center of our solar system", "start": 411.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "emitted powerful radio waves.", "start": 414.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "He had accidentally been the first person", "start": 417.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "to tune in to them.", "start": 420.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Fast-forward 50 years,", "start": 422.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "and Bell and Watson's technology", "start": 424.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "has completely transformed", "start": 427.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "global communications.", "start": 429.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "But going from slinging some wire", "start": 431.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "across rooftops in Boston", "start": 433.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to laying thousands and thousands of miles of cable", "start": 435.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "on the Atlantic Ocean seabed", "start": 438.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "is no easy matter.", "start": 440.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "And so before long,", "start": 442.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Bell were looking to new technologies", "start": 444.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to optimize their revolution.", "start": 446.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "Radio could carry sound without wires.", "start": 449.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "But the medium is lossy --", "start": 452.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "it's subject to a lot of noise and interference.", "start": 454.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "So Bell employed an engineer", "start": 458.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to study those noises,", "start": 460.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to try and find out where they came from,", "start": 462.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "with a view towards building", "start": 464.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "the perfect hardware codec, which would get rid of them", "start": 466.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "so they could think about using radio", "start": 469.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "for the purposes of telephony.", "start": 471.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "Most of the noises", "start": 474.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "that the engineer, Karl Jansky, investigated", "start": 476.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "were fairly prosaic in origin.", "start": 479.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "They turned out to be lightning", "start": 481.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "or sources of electrical power.", "start": 483.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "But there was one persistent noise", "start": 486.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "that Jansky couldn't identify,", "start": 489.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "and it seemed to appear", "start": 491.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "in his radio headset", "start": 493.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "four minutes earlier each day.", "start": 495.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "Now any astronomer will tell you,", "start": 498.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "this is the telltale sign", "start": 500.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "of something that doesn't originate from Earth.", "start": 502.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "Jansky had made a historic discovery,", "start": 505.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "that celestial objects could emit radio waves", "start": 509.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "as well as light waves.", "start": 512.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Fifty years on", "start": 514.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "from Watson's accidental encounter with the Sun,", "start": 516.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "Jansky's careful listening", "start": 519.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "ushered in a new age of space exploration:", "start": 521.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "the radio astronomy age.", "start": 524.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Over the next few years,", "start": 526.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "astronomers connected up their antennas to loudspeakers", "start": 528.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "and learned about our radio sky,", "start": 532.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "about Jupiter and the Sun,", "start": 534.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "by listening.", "start": 536.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Let's jump ahead again.", "start": 538.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "It's 1964,", "start": 540.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "and we're back at Bell Labs.", "start": 542.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "And once again,", "start": 544.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "two scientists have got a problem with noise.", "start": 546.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "Arno Penzias and Robert Wilson", "start": 549.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "were using the horn antenna", "start": 552.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "at Bell's Holmdel laboratory", "start": 554.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to study the Milky Way", "start": 556.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "with extraordinary precision.", "start": 558.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "They were really listening", "start": 560.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "to the galaxy in high fidelity.", "start": 562.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "There was a glitch in their soundtrack.", "start": 564.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "A mysterious persistent noise", "start": 567.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "was disrupting their research.", "start": 570.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "It was in the microwave range,", "start": 572.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "and it appeared to be coming", "start": 574.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "from all directions simultaneously.", "start": 576.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "Now this didn't make any sense,", "start": 578.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "and like any reasonable engineer or scientist,", "start": 580.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "they assumed that the problem must be the technology itself,", "start": 583.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "it must be the dish.", "start": 586.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "There were pigeons roosting in the dish.", "start": 588.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "And so perhaps once they cleaned up the pigeon droppings,", "start": 591.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "get the disk kind of operational again,", "start": 594.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "normal operations would resume.", "start": 596.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "But the noise didn't disappear.", "start": 599.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "The mysterious noise", "start": 602.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "that Penzias and Wilson were listening to", "start": 604.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "turned out to be the oldest and most significant sound", "start": 607.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "that anyone had ever heard.", "start": 610.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "It was cosmic radiation", "start": 612.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "left over from the very birth of the universe.", "start": 614.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "This was the first experimental evidence", "start": 618.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "that the Big Bang existed", "start": 621.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "and the universe was born at a precise moment", "start": 623.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "some 14.7 billion years ago.", "start": 626.26, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "So our story ends", "start": 631.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "at the beginning --", "start": 633.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "the beginning of all things, the Big Bang.", "start": 635.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "This is the noise that Penzias and Wilson heard --", "start": 638.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "the oldest sound that you're ever going to hear,", "start": 641.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "the cosmic microwave background radiation", "start": 644.26, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "left over from the Big Bang.", "start": 647.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "(Fuzz)", "start": 649.26, "duration": 15.0}, {"text": "Thanks.", "start": 664.26, "duration": 2.0}, {"text": "(Applause)", "start": 666.26, "duration": 4.0}]